For comparison with the literature~\cite{TauPol,TauPol2},
it is useful to make a transformation of the parameter space 
$(\theta, \overline \phi, m_{\nu\mu})$ into the alternative parametrization
$(\overline x, \overline \phi, m_{\nu\mu})$, where $\overline x$ is the visible fraction
of the tau lepton energy in the laboratory frame.
The relation between $\overline x$ and $\theta$ can be obtained
by solving for the visible energy $\overline {E}_{vis}$ in the laboratory
frame after a Lorentz boost
$\gamma\equiv 1/(1-\beta^2)^{\frac{1}{2}}=\overline{E}_{\tau}/m_{\tau}$
from the rest frame:
\begin{equation} \label{eq:cosTheta}
 \cos \theta = \frac{ \overline{E}_{vis} - \gamma E_{vis}}{\gamma \beta p_{vis}},
\end{equation}
where $p_{vis} = \sqrt{E_{vis}^2 - m_{vis}^2}$, and $E_{vis}$ is provided
by Eq. \eqref{eq:evis}. In the collinear limit $\beta\to 1$, and neglecting
the mass of the charged leptons ($m_{\ell}/m_{\tau} \sim 0$), Eq. \ref{eq:cosTheta}
simplifies to 
\begin{equation} \label{eq:cosThetaCollHad}
 \cos\theta = \frac{2x-1-m^2_{vis(\nu\nu)}/m^2_{\tau}}{1-m^2_{vis(\nu\nu)}/m^2_{\tau}},
\end{equation}
for a semi--leptonic (fully--leptonic) tau decay.
Equation \eqref{eq:cosThetaCollHad} shows a linear dependence
between $\cos\theta$ and $\overline x$.

Notice that the purely geometrical bound $-1\leq \cos\theta \leq 1$ implies the following
physical constraints:
for the semi--leptonic tau decays, $m_{vis}^2/m_{\tau}^2 \leq \overline x \leq 1$;
for the fully--leptonic tau decays,
$0 \leq \overline x \leq 1$ and $0 \leq m_{\nu\nu} \leq m_{\tau}\sqrt{1-\overline x}$.

